---
const faqs = [
  {
    q: 'How accurate is the dog age calculator?',
    a: 'Our calculator is highly accurate because it uses the latest DNA methylation formula (16 × ln(dog age) + 31) combined with breed size adjustments. This scientific method aligns a dog\'s biological aging clock with human aging far better than the old multiply-by-7 rule.'
  },
  {
    q: 'Do small dogs live longer than large dogs?',
    a: 'Yes, small dogs typically live significantly longer than large and giant breeds. A small breed can live 12-16 years, whereas a giant breed averages 7-10 years. Scientists believe this is because larger dogs experience accelerated growth early in life, leading to faster cellular aging.'
  },
  {
    q: 'What is the oldest dog ever recorded?',
    a: 'The oldest dog ever reliably recorded was an Australian Cattle Dog named Bluey, who lived to be 29 years and 5 months old. More recently, a Rafeiro do Alentejo named Bobi was reported to have lived over 30 years, though Guinness World Records later suspended this title pending investigation.'
  },
  {
    q: 'How do I know what life stage my dog is in?',
    a: 'A dog\'s life stage depends on both their age and breed size. Generally, dogs under 1 year are puppies or teenagers. From 1 to 6 years, most are adults. Large breeds enter their senior years around age 7, while small breeds might not be considered seniors until they are 11 or 12.'
  },
  {
    q: 'Is the multiply by 7 rule accurate?',
    a: 'No, the old rule of multiplying a dog\'s age by 7 is completely inaccurate. Dogs age much faster in their first two years of life than humans do, and their aging slows down later. The 7-year rule was created as a simple marketing myth, not based on science.'
  },
  {
    q: 'What does DNA methylation have to do with dog aging?',
    a: 'DNA methylation is a biological process where chemical tags are added to DNA over time. Researchers from UC San Diego discovered that dogs and humans share similar methylation patterns as they age. This "epigenetic clock" allows scientists to create a highly accurate formula comparing dog aging directly to human aging.'
  },
  {
    q: 'How often should I recalculate my dog\'s age?',
    a: 'You should recalculate your dog\'s age whenever they reach a new milestone, such as a birthday or half-birthday. Because dogs age much faster than humans (especially in their early years), their human-equivalent age can jump significantly in just a few months.'
  },
  {
    q: 'Does breed affect how fast a dog ages?',
    a: 'Absolutely. Breed size is the most significant factor in a dog\'s aging rate. Giant breeds like Great Danes age the fastest, becoming seniors by age 6. Small breeds like Chihuahuas age the slowest, often staying energetic and youthful well into their teens.'
  }
];
---

<section class="w-full max-w-2xl mx-auto" aria-labelledby="faq-heading">
  <h2 id="faq-heading" class="text-xl sm:text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-[var(--text-primary)] mb-6 sm:mb-8">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="space-y-4 sm:space-y-6" id="faq-container">
    {faqs.map((faq, i) => (
      <div class="faq-item card p-4.5 sm:p-4 md:p-6 cursor-pointer" data-index={i}>
        <button class="flex items-center justify-between gap-4 w-full text-left cursor-pointer bg-transparent border-0 p-0" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls={`faq-answer-${i}`} id={`faq-btn-${i}`}>
          <span class="text-sm sm:text-[0.9375rem] font-medium text-[var(--text-primary)] leading-relaxed pr-2">{faq.q}</span>
          <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-[var(--text-faint)] shrink-0 transition-transform duration-300" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true" focusable="false"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer overflow-hidden transition-all duration-300" style="max-height: 0; opacity: 0;" role="region" aria-labelledby={`faq-btn-${i}`} id={`faq-answer-${i}`}>
          <p class="mt-4 text-sm text-[var(--text-secondary)] leading-relaxed">{faq.a}</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    ))}
  </div>
</section>

<script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": faqs.map(f => ({
    "@type": "Question",
    "name": f.q,
    "acceptedAnswer": {
      "@type": "Answer",
      "text": f.a
    }
  })),
  "author": {
    "@type": "Organization",
    "name": "DOGBREEDAGE",
    "url": "https://dogbreedage.com"
  },
  "publisher": {
    "@type": "Organization",
    "name": "DOGBREEDAGE",
    "url": "https://dogbreedage.com"
  },
  "datePublished": "2025-01-15",
  "dateModified": new Date().toISOString().split('T')[0]
})} />

<script>
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
  document.querySelectorAll('.faq-item').forEach(item => {
    const btn = item.querySelector('button');
    const answer = item.querySelector('.faq-answer');
    const icon = item.querySelector('svg');

    function toggleFaq() {
      const expanded = btn.getAttribute('aria-expanded') === 'true';
      btn.setAttribute('aria-expanded', String(!expanded));
      if (expanded) {
        answer.style.maxHeight = '0';
        answer.style.opacity = '0';
        icon.style.transform = 'rotate(0deg)';
      } else {
        answer.style.maxHeight = answer.scrollHeight + 'px';
        answer.style.opacity = '1';
        icon.style.transform = 'rotate(180deg)';
      }
    }

    // Make entire card clickable, not just the button
    item.addEventListener('click', (e) => {
      // Prevent double-firing if the click was on a link inside the answer
      if (e.target.closest('a')) return;
      toggleFaq();
    });
  });
});
</script>
